{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 10:39:56.484127", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report — Clos EBGP Lab\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Host-level connectivity between pc_0_0 and pc_0_1 is functional (bi-directional pings succeeded with 0% loss).\\n- Control-plane anomaly: spine_router_0_1 is not establishing BGP peering sessions and is not learning/advertising the /24 prefixes. This is isolated to spine_router_0_1; other routers (spine_router_0_0, leaves, super-spine) have working EBGP adjacencies and route visibility.\\n- Likely root cause: misconfiguration of spine_router_0_1’s BGP local AS (shows 65701) causing EBGP neighbor AS mismatch and sessions to remain in Idle. Effect: loss of one spine’s participation in routing and reduced redundancy (all prefixes are being learned via spine_router_0_0).\\n\\nEvidence and findings\\n\\n1) Host reachability (control test)\\n- From aggregated reachability: pc_0_0 -> pc_0_1: tx 2 rx 2 loss 0%; avg RTT ~3.29 ms\\n- pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0: tx 2 rx 2 loss 0%; avg RTT ~1.85 ms\\nInterpretation: L2/L3 forwarding between hosts works; user-plane traffic is passing end-to-end.\\n\\n2) BGP prefix/routing visibility (selected excerpts)\\n- leaf_router_0_0 BGP table\\n  - Locally connected: 10.0.0.0/24 (local)\\n  - Learned: 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.4 (path 65100 65201)\\n- leaf_router_0_1 BGP table\\n  - Locally connected: 10.0.1.0/24 (local)\\n  - Learned: 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.6 (path 65100 65200)\\n- spine_router_0_0 BGP table\\n  - Learns 10.0.0.0/24 via 172.16.0.5 (65200)\\n  - Learns 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.7 (65201)\\n- super_spine_router_0 BGP table\\n  - Learns both 10.0.0.0/24 and 10.0.1.0/24 via 172.16.0.1\\n  - (172.16.0.1 is the next-hop used by the super-spine for both prefixes — i.e., only one spine is advertising upward)\\n\\n3) Spine router 0_1 — control-plane failure and misconfiguration (concrete evidence)\\n- show ip bgp summary (spine_router_0_1)\\n  - BGP router identifier 172.16.0.3, local AS number 65701\\n  - Peers listed (example): 172.16.0.2 (AS 65000), 172.16.0.9 (AS 65200), 172.16.0.11 (AS 65201)\\n  - For all neighbors: State = Idle, PfxRcd = 0\\n  - Total number of neighbors 3\\n- frr_get_bgp_conf / BGP table for spine_router_0_1\\n  - \"No BGP prefixes displayed, 0 exist\"\\n- ip route (spine_router_0_1)\\n  - Only shows connected /31s; no BGP-learned 10.0.0.0/24 or 10.0.1.0/24\\n\\nInterpretation:\\n- spine_router_0_1 reports a local AS of 65701 (printed in the BGP summary). The expected spine AS (from the topology and other spine_router_0_0 output) is 65100. Because EBGP requires the neighbor AS to match the configured remote AS, a wrong local AS will cause AS mismatch with neighbors -> BGP sessions never establish (Idle state).\\n- The Idle state and PfxRcd = 0 confirm the sessions are not up; consequently, spine_router_0_1 is not advertising/receiving the end-host /24 prefixes into/from the fabric.\\n- The super-spine is learning both prefixes via a single spine (spine_router_0_0) as shown by both prefixes pointing to the same next-hop (172.16.0.1). This indicates the fabric’s redundancy is degraded: one spine (spine_router_0_1) is out of the EBGP control plane.\\n\\nLocalization (faulty device(s))\\n- Primary faulty device: spine_router_0_1 (BGP sessions Idle, BGP local AS = 65701, no BGP routes present).\\n- No evidence of similar failures on spine_router_0_0, leaves, or super_spine_router_0 — their BGP tables show expected prefixes and routes.\\n\\nRoot cause analysis\\n- Direct cause: BGP neighbor establishment failure on spine_router_0_1 resulting in Idle state for all neighbors.\\n- Most probable root configuration error: Incorrect BGP local AS configured on spine_router_0_1 (65701) causing an AS mismatch with expected EBGP neighbors (expected AS for spines: 65100). This prevents session formation and prevents propagation of the leaf /24 prefixes via that spine.\\n- Secondary effect: Loss of path redundancy and concentration of prefix advertisement through the remaining functional spine (spine_router_0_0). While host reachability remains functional (alternate path exists), the control-plane state shows the network is no longer fully redundant.\\n\\nAdditional notes\\n- There are normal-looking BGP adjacencies and routes on leaf_router_0_0, leaf_router_0_1, spine_router_0_0, and super_spine_router_0.\\n- The fact that end-host ping tests succeed demonstrates that data-plane forwarding still has a viable path via the remaining spine(s), so immediate host outage is avoided; however, the topology is operating with reduced resilience.\\n\\nConclusion\\n- The network exhibits a clear BGP control-plane anomaly localized to spine_router_0_1: its BGP neighbors are Idle and it carries no BGP prefixes. The most likely single root cause is a misconfigured local AS (65701) on spine_router_0_1 causing EBGP neighbor mismatch.\\n- Impact: loss of one spine from the EBGP routing domain, reduced redundancy, and potential traffic concentration on the remaining spine.\\n\\nIf you want, I can next:\\n- show the exact BGP configuration on spine_router_0_1 (to confirm the misconfigured AS and neighbor statements),\\n- display detailed neighbor logs for spine_router_0_1,\\n- or collect the exact BGP configuration files used on all routers for cross-checking.\\n\\n(Per your instructions, I have not included mitigation steps in this report.), please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='d089e0fc-cda7-46a6-afde-4922741850c3'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
